Here’s how you can implement the `list` command to display all allowed environment variables and their current values or a fallback message if they’re not configured.

**cmd/list.go:**
```go
package cmd

import (
	"github.com/spf13/cobra"
	"my-env-tool/utils"
	"os"
	"fmt"
)

var listCmd = &cobra.Command{
	Use:   "list",
	Short: "List all allowed environment variables and their values",
	Run: func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) {
		config, err := utils.LoadConfig("config/default.yaml")
		if err != nil {
			fmt.Println("Failed to load configuration:", err)
			return
		}

		allowedVars := config["allowed_variables"].([]interface{})
		fmt.Println("Allowed environment variables:")
		for _, v := range allowedVars {
			key := v.(string)
			value, exists := os.LookupEnv(key)
			if exists {
				fmt.Printf("%s=%s\n", key, value)
			} else {
				fmt.Printf("%s=unset\n", key)
			}
		}
	},
}

func init() {
	rootCmd.AddCommand(listCmd)
}
```

This command loads the `allowed_variables` list from the YAML configuration file and iterates over it. For each allowed variable, it checks whether the variable is set using `os.LookupEnv`. If it’s set, the current value is printed; otherwise, it prints `unset`.

